New Picto-Interview: we talked with Luke Pearson about how thinking of Hilda 24/7 has impacted his life, the particular, quiet weirdness of old Scandinavian folklore, and why, when he reads comics, he feels quite detached.

pictoplasma.com/c-files

New C(haracter)-File on our PictoBlog: Shortly before publicly announcing the discontinuation of the #Hilda series we met up with Luke Pearson at his Pictoplasma exhibition to talk about elves and trolls, the genesis of his graphic novel, the intimidating move from the books to an international TV series, and the different levels of scariness in both media. 👉 pictoplasma.com/c-files

Carpe Diem! 
Just wanted to wish you all a lovely day and share this good-looking late #2cute2fail entry  by @peterjavidpour on Pictofolio.com

FREE PictoTalk of the week: Jeron Braxton, animator genius exploring the Black American experience via surreal Playstation 2 aesthetics, as he shares valuable insight, gives advice and shows surprising dance moves. Free grab only this week 👉 pictoplasma.com/pictotalks/ … (BTW: Tickets for our upcoming 16th #PictoplasmaBerlin 2020 available at berlin.pictoplasma.com )

And that's a wrap! The #2cute2fail challenge may now 'officially' be over (huge THANK YOU to all who've provided character solace + special ❤️ to our challenge partner @clipstudioofficial 🙌 ), but rest assured... Pictofolio.com remains open 24/7 for all your character needs, currently housing 17000+ empathic visuals and their skilled creators.

Good Sunday reading: ‘Into the Spider-Verse’ production designer Justin K. Thompson on taking a leap of faith to rather fail at something new, than create something you're not passionate about, and the never changing rules of composition and design, shape and form, lighting and color... pictoplasma.com/interview/justin-thompson/

Good Sunday reading: we talked with Philippa Rice about her desperate for attention family of crochet characters, the benefits of keeping a diary, and why she makes sure her partner Luke Pearson is happy with her comics before they’re released... but he always is.

New C(haracter)-File on our PictoBlog: We talked to #1 NewYorkTimes bestselling author Philippa Rice about her growing family of crochet characters,  the difficulties of finding the right work/life balance with her partner Luke Pearson, and her now released ‘BABY: A Soppy Story,’ a collection of intimate vignettes about a couple expecting their first baby. 🍼 pictoplasma.com/c-files
